qa_data = {
    "what is the sant nirankari mission": "The Sant Nirankari Mission is a spiritual organization founded in 1929 by Baba Buta Singh Ji Maharaj, that aims to promote universal brotherhood and peace by helping people realize God through the guidance of a living Satguru. The mission has grown into a global organisation under the divine leadership of successive spiritual guides (Sadguru), including Shehanshah Baba Avtar Singh Ji, Baba Gurubachan Singh Ji, Baba Hardev Singh Ji, Mata Savinder Ji, and now Sadguru Mata Sudiksha Ji Maharaj.",
    "what is the main message of the sant nirankari mission": "The mission teaches that God is formless and omnipresent, and every human being can experience God-realisation in their lifetime through the Satguru’s grace. Its core values are love, humility, unity, and service.",
    "who is the current spiritual head of the mission": "As of now, the spiritual head is Satguru Mata Sudiksha Ji Maharaj, who is leading the mission with a focus on youth empowerment, devotion, and social welfare.",
    "what is meant by god-realisation in this mission": "God-Realisation means experiencing and becoming aware of the formless God (Nirankar) within and around us. This is made possible by the Satguru during a spiritual revelation (Gyan).",
    "what is the role of the satguru in the sant nirankari mission": "The Satguru is the enlightened master who grants God-knowledge and guides followers on how to live a truthful and spiritual life filled with love, service, and devotion.",
    "what are the key practices of the mission": "The mission emphasizes three main practices:\n• Sewa (selfless service)\n• Simran (constant remembrance of Nirankar)\n• Satsang (attending spiritual gatherings for growth and unity)",
    "does the sant nirankari mission follow a particular religion": "No. The mission respects all religions and does not promote conversion. It focuses on spirituality and humanity, encouraging people of all backgrounds to come together in peace.",
    "what is the purpose of satsang in the mission": "Satsang is a spiritual congregation where followers come together to listen to discourses, sing devotional hymns, and strengthen their connection with God and one another.",
    "what social work does the mission do": "The mission organizes blood donation drives, tree plantation, cleanliness campaigns, disaster relief, health camps, and youth development programs as part of its “Manav Sewa is Madhav Sewa” belief (serving humanity is serving God).",
    "what does nirankar mean": "“Nirankar” means formless God—the eternal, omnipresent divine power that cannot be seen with physical eyes but can be experienced through divine knowledge (Brahmgyan) granted by the Satguru.",
    "what is brahmgyan": "Brahmgyan is the realisation of the formless God that is given directly by the Satguru. It is not theoretical, but a practical experience that changes one’s vision of life and brings peace, clarity, and spiritual awakening.",
    "how does the mission help in day-to-day life": "The teachings help individuals to live a peaceful, ego-free, and balanced life. They encourage forgiveness, self-discipline, positive thinking, and service to others, which improves personal and social life.",
    "what role do youth play in the mission": "Youth are seen as the future of the Mission and society. Special platforms like Nirankari Youth Symposiums, Sewadal Training, and Yuvak Mandals are organized to engage youth in spirituality, leadership, and service.",
    "what is nirankari sewadal": "The Sant Nirankari Sewadal (SNSD) is a disciplined group of volunteers of the Sant Nirankari Mission dedicated to the selfless service of the humankind. These volunteers come from different backgrounds of the society.\nIt was in 1956 that Baba Avtar Singh ji established Sewadal. Within a little time of it’s coming to form, Nirankari Rajmata ji led to the establishment of the women’s wing of the Sewadal. Since then, its volunteers have been participating in the Mission’s activities and through them, selflessly serving the humanity at large.\n‘Nar Sewa, Narayan pooja’. Serving the creation of God is serving God himself; and it is while serving selflessly that the ego is shed. And all that remains is a sense of contentment and divine bliss.\nWith this noble belief, lakhs of selfless sewadars (volunteers) of the Sewadal, all across the world, tirelessly work throughout the year with the blessings of Satguru. Working as a backbone of the mission, the Sant Nirankari Sewa Dal plays a crucial role in managing and giving shape to the spiritual congregations, various events and philanthropic activities undertaken and organized by the Sant Nirankari Mission.",
    "what is the nirankari sant samagam": "The gathering of Mission’s devotees in large numbers periodically to celebrate the essence of enlightenment; also intending to share it with other brothers and sisters across the world is what we know as Samagam. Nirankari Samagams have become synonymous with selfless service, discipline, togetherness along with spiritual and ethical discourse, everything contributing to manifest a blissful festival of brotherhood in the most quintessential way. In no uncertain terms, these Samagams are microcosms of ‘Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam’, which literally means ‘The whole world is our family’.",
    "how can someone join the sant nirankari mission": "Anyone can join by attending Satsang gatherings, meeting a Gyan Pracharak, and receiving Brahmgyan from the Satguru’s representative. There is no conversion, and all are welcomed with love.",
    "does the mission encourage education and careers": "Absolutely. The Mission believes in balancing spiritual and worldly responsibilities. It encourages followers to study, work honestly, and succeed in life while staying grounded in values.",
    "what is the sant nirankari charitable foundation": "The Sant Nirankari Charitable Foundation (SNCF) goes beyond just charity. Our mission is to spread kindness and care throughout the world, building a better society for those in need. Founded in 2010 to implement the vision of Nirankari Baba Ji, “Life gets a meaning, if it is lived for others”, SNCF focuses on social and charitable work. Our organisation is guided by the principle of Service with Humility. This mission statement shapes our work across three key areas: social responsibility, environmental initiatives, and healthcare programs.",
    "what are the core values of sncf": "Heal, Enrich & Empower are three core values of SNCF.\n1. HEAL (Health) - SNCF improves healthcare through hospitals, blood banks, and clinics, also working on environmental healing.\n2. ENRICH (Education) - Through schools, training centers, libraries, hostels etc.\n3. EMPOWER (Upliftment) - Youth/women empowerment, workshops, disaster relief, elder care, and disability support.",
    "what are the spiritual text of nirankari mission": "Spiritual texts have played an integral role in the enlightenment of man. The two spiritual texts of the Mission continue to guide and enlighten human mind towards the path of salvation and righteousness: Sampurna Avtar Bani & Sampurna Hardev Bani.",
    "what is avtar bani": "Scripted and blessed by Baba Avtar Singh Ji, Sampuran Avtar Vani is a collection of 376 pious verses that gently take a seeker from the state of oblivion to the identity of being One with One. Originally in Punjabi, it's translated into many languages including English, Hindi, Marathi, Gujarati, Bengali etc.",
    "what is hardev bani": "A gift of Baba Hardev Singh Ji to humanity, the Sampuran Hardev Vani is a collection of 301 sacred verses, originally scripted in Hindi, that deal with many contemporary issues. It captures the essence of Baba Ji’s discourses and wisdom.",
    "what are the magazines and literature of nirankari mission": "Ek Nazar, Sant Nirankari, and Hansti Duniya are regular magazines published in many languages. Numerous books have been published by Nirankari Publications covering history, ideology, activities, spirituality, and social dimensions.",
    "what are the five principles of nirankari mission": "The five pledges are:\n1. Use body, mind, and possessions as blessings without ego.\n2. Avoid ego based on caste, creed, race, etc.\n3. No discrimination based on lifestyle or appearance.\n4. Do not abandon family life; fulfill responsibilities.\n5. Do not share God Knowledge without Master’s consent.",
    "what are the seven stars of nirankari mission": "The first Executive Committee formed in 1948 included:\n1. Shri Labh Singh Ji (President)\n2. Dr. Des Raj Ji (Vice-President)\n3. Shri Ram Saran Ji (Secretary)\n4. Babu Mahadev Singh Ji (Vice-Secretary)\n5. Shri Santokh Singh Ji (Publication)\n6. Shri Jugal Kishore Ji (Treasurer)\n7. Shri Bhagat Ramchandar Ji (Langar In-charge)",
    "what is being nirankari": "We are ‘Nirankari’, meaning we have realized the formless God through Satguru’s grace. Our daily connection is expressed through Simran:\n“Tu Hi Nirankar”\n“Main Teri Sharan Haan”\n“Mainu Baksh Lo”",
    "what is simran in nirankari mission": "“Tu Hi Nirankar”\n“Main Teri Sharan Haan”\n“Mainu Baksh Lo”",
    "what are different samagams in nirankari mission": "Annual Sant Samagam, Bhakti Parv Samagam, Manav Ekta Diwas, Samarpan Diwas, Mukti Parv, and Regional Samagams.",
    "tell me something about annual sant samagam": "Started in 1948, it is now a global spiritual festival attended by lakhs. Held in Samalkha, Haryana, it includes congregations, sewa, langar, exhibitions, and teachings from the Satguru.",
    "what is bhakti parv samagam": "Held in January, Bhakti Parv celebrates devotion. Major gatherings occur near the Sarovar Complex in Delhi. It emphasizes love for Nirankar and detached attachment through teachings, hymns, and holy dips in Sarovar.",
    "what is manav ekta diwas": "Observed on April 24 in memory of Baba Gurbachan Singh Ji’s martyrdom. It promotes unity, blood donation, and remembrance of his teachings and sacrifice along with Chacha Pratap Singh Ji.",
    "what is samarpan diwas": "Held on May 13 in memory of Baba Hardev Singh Ji’s life and teachings. It celebrates his message of oneness, compassion, and global spiritual transformation. Also remembers Avneet Setya Ji.",
    "what is mukti parv": "Observed on August 15, Mukti Parv emphasizes salvation and pays homage to spiritual leaders like Baba Avtar Singh Ji, Mata Budhwanti Ji, and others. It coincides with India’s Independence Day to symbolize spiritual freedom.",
    "what is regional samagam": "Regional Samagams are held throughout India in various states and cities. Despite cultural differences, they showcase oneness through multilingual spiritual expressions, sewa, and teachings led by Satguru’s grace."
}
